<question xmlns="http://www.gradians.com" chapterId="0">
  <statement>
    <tex>%text
Evaluate 
\[ \qquad \sin \left[ \frac\pi{3} - \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2} \right) \right] \] 
%</tex>
  </statement>
  <step>
    <options>
      <tex correct="false">\begin{align}
\sin\left( \pi + \frac\pi{6}\right) &amp;= \sin\left( \frac{7\pi}{6} \right)  = -\frac{1}{2} \\
\therefore \sin^{-1}\left( -\frac{1}{2} \right) &amp;= \frac{7\pi}{6} 
\end{align} </tex>
    </options>
    <reason>
      <tex>%text
There are infinite angles for which 
\[ \qquad \sin\theta = -\frac{1}{2} \]

But when we say \[ \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right) = \theta  \], 
the $\theta$ is an angle in what is called 
\underline\text{the principal range.} 


For $\sin^{-1} x$, that principal range is \[ \left[-\frac\pi{2},\frac\pi{2}\right]\]

And as $\sin\left( -\frac\pi{6}\right) = -\frac{1}{2}$ and $-\frac\pi{6}\in\left[ -\frac\pi{2},\frac\pi{2}\right]$,
\[ \qquad \therefore \sin^{-1}\left( -\frac{1}{2}\right) = -\frac\pi{6} \]
%</tex>
    </reason>
    <skills>
      <skill id="39"/>
    </skills>
  </step>
  <step>
    <options>
      <tex>\[ \sin \left[ \frac\pi{3} - \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2} \right) \right] = 1 \]</tex>
      <tex correct="false">\[ \sin \left[ \frac\pi{3} - \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2} \right) \right] = \frac{1}{2} \]</tex>
    </options>
    <reason>
      <tex>\begin{align}
\sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2}  \right) &amp;= -\frac\pi{6} \\
\therefore \frac\pi{3} - \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2}  \right)  &amp;= \frac\pi{3} - \left( -\frac\pi{6} \right)\\
&amp;= \frac\pi{2} \\
\implies \sin \left[ \frac\pi{3} - \sin^{-1}\left(-\frac{1}{2} \right) \right] &amp;= \sin\frac\pi{2}= 1
\end{align}</tex>
    </reason>
    <skills>
      <skill id="1"/>
    </skills>
  </step>
</question>
